Ecuador: Medical Alert Becomes Health Emergency
-----------------------------------------------
In less than a week, a medical alert became a health emergency due to
detection of 14 cases of dengue hemorrhagic fever (DHF), a number equal to
the total of cases registered in 2002.
Decree number 137, signed on Tuesday night [11 Feb 2003] by Vice-President
Alfredo Palacio, was justified both by the [increased] prevalence of
malaria (1500 cases per province in January) and the fact that DHF was
present not only in Guayas, but also in Los Rios and in Manabi.
Francisco Andino, Minister of Health, stated that the government and the
Solidarity Trust would provide 10 million dollars for the implementation of
emergency measures. Ernesto Gutierrez, Under-Secretary of Tropical
Medicine, stated that during the next few days MODERSA [a Ministry of
Health project for the modernization of health services] would provide one
million dollars.
In addition, a 7-million-dollar plan has been submitted to the same entity.
Among other things, the funds will be destined for the purchase of
pesticides, larvicide, 40 vehicles, and 100 microscopes to be distributed
in a targeted manner.
Andino stated that the purchases will be closely supervised and that a
government representative will administer the applications. A community
leader for each 100 families will be trained for the elimination of
mosquito breeding sites. The Ministry hopes to achieve a 70 to 75 percent
commitment by the community during this year, given that the elimination of
these tropical diseases [dengue fever and malaria] requires at least 5 to 7
years. For its part, the Tropical Medicine Secretariat stated that it would
settle for 120 medical brigades, the design of a treatment protocol,
adequate supplies of medicine, and the recruitment of different hospitals
-- from the Ministry, Naval hospitals, the Welfare Action Force, and the
Society for the Protection of Children -- so that the Hospital for
Infectious Diseases is not overwhelmed with cases. 2 cases are yet to be
confirmed, and 80 percent of the population of the coast is susceptible to
dengue fever.
