Mexico: Epidemiological Alert in the State of Morelos
---------------------------------------------------
Antonio Campos Rendon, Health Secretary of the state of Morelos, announced
that an epidemiological alert had been issued on Thu 13 Feb 2003 for the
whole state and neighboring areas. The measure was taken after 2 cases of
dengue hemorrhagic fever [DHF] were confirmed in the municipality of
Jiutepec. One of the patients, a 45-year-old woman, has died.
During a press conference, the official stated that the cooperation of the
federal health department has been requested to address this suspected
outbreak, given that the contagion occurred in an unexpected manner, that
is, during an atypical time of year.
The patient who died had received private medical attention and later was
hospitalized for 15 days in an intensive care unit. The family has
authorized an autopsy to confirm the diagnosis. The second patient remains
hospitalized in the city of Cuernavaca. The epidemiological alert was
distributed to 33 municipalities of Morelos and neighboring states, and in
particular the municipalities of Jiutepec, Yautepec, Ciudad Ayala, and
Zacatepec, where some of the 91 cases of classic dengue fever were reported
in 2002. During 2002 only 3 cases of DHF were reported in Ciudad Ayala, and
it was established that they had been imported from the state of Michoacan.
The health authorities stated that, in accordance with the permanent
campaign for the control of the disease, in place in the municipality of
Jiutepec since May 2002, 440 houses have been inspected, and fumigation to
exterminate the vector has been carried out on 119 occasions.
Since the detection of the 2 cases, approximately 17 persons have been
examined and are currently under observation. Campos Rendon said that it is
expected that this year there may be an increase in the number of cases,
since specialized research indicates that every 5 years or so, time and the
use of pesticides make the vector stronger.
Around September 2002, the Epidemiology Department of the Health
Secretariat in Morelos reported 175 probable cases of dengue fever. Over
the past 5 years, Morelos has seen a reduction in the area of incidence of
the disease. 10 years ago, cases were detected in 22 of the 33
municipalities, whereas last year, cases were detected in only 11
localities, almost all of them in urban and semi rural zones.
[Byline: Raquel Fierro]
